The temporal memory [performance test](https://github.com/numenta/nupic/blob/master/tests/integration/nupic/algorithms/temporal_memory_performance_test.py) passes unreliably in CI and locally. Sometimes the test fails to show that the C++ TM is faster than python. See for instance [this build failure](https://ci.appveyor.com/project/numenta-ci/nupic/build/0.1.0.1008). This should be further investigated. However, it is possible that these failures are not symptomatic of worse performance of the C++ implementation and rather are due to random fluctuations of the server load affecting the real time it takes to run each of the TM implementations. If this is the case, one possible solution is to train each model for only one time step in each iteration of the outer loop over time steps, rather than the current test that fully trains each model before proceeding to the next model. This proposal in pseudocode: 
```python
for record in records:
  for model in models:
    times[model] += real time of model.compute(record)
```
This would reduce the tendency for fluctuations in server load to bias the results of the test.

